-- #784 (S0, ratified 2026-07-20, Option A): an interface method whose signature
-- carries a FREE, RETURN-POSITION effect var — `speak : a -> <e> String`, where
-- `e` is determined only by which impl DISPATCH picks, not by any argument —
-- LAUNDERS its effect. `pureUse` below is declared PURE (no `<e>`) yet its body
-- calls `speak`, which dispatches to `Speak Dog`'s impl that performs <Stdout>
-- (`putStr`). Pre-fix, check/run/build ACCEPTED (exit 0) and running printed
-- "[call] woof" — IO from a function the type system certifies pure, the silent
-- effect-laundering hole. Option A rejects the under-determined return-only
-- effect var as ill-formed at the INTERFACE DECLARATION (T-EFFECT-UNDETERMINED),
-- upstream of any impl, so check == run == build all REJECT via a DIAGNOSTIC
-- (never a runtime panic). This drained #784. Argument-carried effect vars
-- (map/fold/traverse) are pinned by a callback and are NOT rejected.
interface Speak a where
  speak : a -> <e> String

data Dog = Dog

impl Speak Dog where
  speak d =
    let _ = putStr "[call] "
    "woof"

pureUse : Speak a => a -> String
pureUse x = speak x

main = putStrLn (pureUse Dog)
